Text: We had our first meeting with our client this week.
I was afraid of one thing - and that was the impending awkward silences that would fill the zoom meeting.
One thing I was hoping for, was that the client would have so much input and ideas that she would mostly talk without the need for our probing.
However, that was not quite how it went, which is no surprise really, because a conversation is two way.
I felt really bad that I wasn't communicating effortlessly, mainly because of nerves and because I felt super inexperienced.
However, better preparation will definitely be a goal of mine next time.
Communicating with clients and people in general is very important so this is something I definitely need to work on.
Despite this, the main thing I got out of the interview was that they desired a technical aspect in the collections area of the museum (where it is free), so that museum-goers can engage more.
The engagement was to be encouraged by interacting with people's own devices, but a possible idea of the museum providing their own devices in the future if they had funding.
URL codes, according to Hannah was a huge no-no, but she also liked the idea of some sort of reader, scanner or geo fencing by sending a notification to the device of a visitor.
All these ideas sounded awesome, but I couldn't help but feel exactly the same as Hannah, I had no idea how these all worked.
I had little confidence in myself because I wasn't sure how these concepts all worked or if they were simple enough to do.
My team mates are great, very relaxed, very unproblematic.
However, the worst thing about introverts is that we can be a little too quiet.
Although we're all a little quiet, things still get done, which is great, however, I wish they would verbally communicate their thoughts more freely so I knew I was on the same page as them.
I suppose, this is something else I have to navigate.
At the end of the day, we still work well together and communicate on a variety of platforms (Discord and Slack).
I am excited (and nervous) to see what the week ahead has in store for us!
We settled on NFC because Bibi suggested that it would be the easiest thing to do.
Naturally, I thought this was a great idea because he is an experienced programmer.
The presentation result was a success in my eyes.
A lot of feedback from Mimi, which was needed because initially, we were very unsureÂ of the path to take in terms of our project proposal.
It helped us solidify and narrow the basics of our ideas more.
We will be meeting on Monday to plan out our tasks and roles for the week and meet again on Friday to chat about our progress - so in terms of project goals, that will be discussed on Monday.

My goal for next week is to carry a tonne of research in terms of our project - mainly working on becoming proficient at Github, researching how NFC works, researching wed design theories and how to use HTML and CSS.
I think Bibi will be giving the group a little tutorial on Github, so this will be very helpful!
A big aspect too is figuring out how to manage a project like this.
I can't wait to just get started and get my hands dirty so this project is fleshed out in my mind more.
